1
00:00:39,610 --> 00:00:41,240
T-This is so spectacular.

2
00:00:41,260 --> 00:00:42,660
I truly didn't expect it.

3
00:00:48,320 --> 00:00:49,530
Ten years...

4
00:00:51,210 --> 00:00:53,940
I've finally gotten into
the Southern Archives.

5
00:00:54,600 --> 00:00:55,400
Ten years.

6
00:00:57,810 --> 00:01:00,180
What exactly

7
00:01:01,340 --> 00:01:03,390
does the Southern Archives do?

8
00:01:04,250 --> 00:01:05,280
The Southern Archives

9
00:01:05,280 --> 00:01:06,580
collects records of
all the strange and mysterious events

10
00:01:06,580 --> 00:01:08,850
that occur throughout
the southern regions of our country.

11
00:01:08,850 --> 00:01:10,039
It's a secret organization

12
00:01:10,039 --> 00:01:12,300
under the Maritime Supervisory Office.

13
00:01:12,990 --> 00:01:14,850
At least, that's what I believed.

14
00:01:15,770 --> 00:01:17,930
Maritime Supervisory Office?

15
00:01:19,060 --> 00:01:20,670
You really are a cop.

16
00:01:21,430 --> 00:01:23,240
Cousin, I've been so good to you,

17
00:01:23,260 --> 00:01:24,990
and you still don't believe me?

18
00:01:25,539 --> 00:01:27,300
It's because you've been too good to me,

19
00:01:27,300 --> 00:01:28,120
and I trusted you like an idiot.

20
00:01:28,120 --> 00:01:30,280
Look at my neck, my face, and my hand.

21
00:01:30,840 --> 00:01:31,860
Alright, just tell me

22
00:01:31,860 --> 00:01:33,990
what we're looking for. I'll help you.

23
00:01:35,250 --> 00:01:36,460
No destroying anything, though.

24
00:01:36,460 --> 00:01:37,460
I'm watching you.

25
00:01:39,090 --> 00:01:40,009
Right now, we need to find

26
00:01:40,009 --> 00:01:41,410
something very special.

27
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:43,789
Something special?

28
00:01:53,140 --> 00:01:55,200
Everything's arranged so randomly.

29
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:06,980
Did you find anything?

30
00:02:08,100 --> 00:02:08,940
No!

31
00:02:13,250 --> 00:02:14,310
[Name: Zhang Hairu] [Name: Zhang Haimo]

32
00:02:14,340 --> 00:02:15,220
[Name: Zhang Haimo]
[Case: Jiulong River Shipwreck Incident]

33
00:02:15,240 --> 00:02:17,000
[Name: Zhang Hailou]
[Case: Panhua Reef Case]

34
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,350
[Note: Risk of exposing
the Southern Archives.]

35
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:28,780
I mean, has this place...

36
00:02:29,630 --> 00:02:31,190
ever really been in operation?

37
00:02:31,190 --> 00:02:32,850
What kind of question is that?

38
00:02:33,190 --> 00:02:34,630
With this many archives,

39
00:02:35,150 --> 00:02:37,470
if they weren't organized
according to some system,

40
00:02:37,470 --> 00:02:39,530
the place couldn't possibly operate.

41
00:02:39,530 --> 00:02:41,780
Unless someone has a photographic memory,

42
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:43,280
there's no way to

43
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:44,400
cross-check all these files,

44
00:02:44,400 --> 00:02:45,740
let alone file them properly.

45
00:02:45,740 --> 00:02:46,670
Time.

46
00:02:47,930 --> 00:02:49,060
Can you

47
00:02:49,079 --> 00:02:51,430
give me a full sentence?

48
00:02:51,530 --> 00:02:54,410
My mentor said
ordinary people might not understand,

49
00:02:54,410 --> 00:02:56,410
but she had all the time in the world.

50
00:02:56,810 --> 00:02:57,930
You mean

51
00:02:57,960 --> 00:03:02,910
your mentor said
she could memorize all of these?

52
00:03:03,910 --> 00:03:05,300
That's impossible.

53
00:03:05,580 --> 00:03:07,670
Even a lifetime wouldn't be enough

54
00:03:07,690 --> 00:03:10,290
for an ordinary person
to memorize all of this.

55
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:17,900
[Telegraph Office, Branch No. 05]

56
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,200
I knew there was this telegraph office.

57
00:03:20,250 --> 00:03:21,620
No way my memory was off.

58
00:03:32,900 --> 00:03:34,370
Five, four, nine...

59
00:03:36,760 --> 00:03:37,850
Five, four, nine?

60
00:03:38,630 --> 00:03:39,760
Five, four, nine...

61
00:03:44,970 --> 00:03:45,630
Found it?

62
00:04:01,250 --> 00:04:02,560
The first medicinal herb.

63
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:03,570
Two more to go.

64
00:04:03,670 --> 00:04:04,640
Is this it?

65
00:04:07,510 --> 00:04:08,910
Such an important thing,

66
00:04:09,030 --> 00:04:10,960
a-and it's just kept in a file bag?

67
00:04:13,210 --> 00:04:14,270
Reverse thinking.

68
00:04:14,320 --> 00:04:15,400
The more important something is,

69
00:04:15,400 --> 00:04:16,660
the more it should be kept
in an inconspicuous place.

70
00:04:16,660 --> 00:04:18,740
That way, it's less likely
to attract attention.

71
00:04:18,740 --> 00:04:20,500
T-That's all there is to it?

72
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:22,620
You think that's simple?

73
00:04:23,040 --> 00:04:25,100
I probably would've thought so once.

74
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:26,780
But not anymore.

75
00:04:31,950 --> 00:04:34,070
Southern Archives:

76
00:04:34,070 --> 00:04:36,570
Director, one. Administrator, one.

77
00:04:36,570 --> 00:04:37,930
Inspector, one.

78
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:41,390
In addition, Commissioners,
Vice Commissioners, and others

79
00:04:41,390 --> 00:04:43,860
assigned to patrol
the Nanyang coastal areas

80
00:04:43,860 --> 00:04:44,750
have no fixed number,

81
00:04:44,750 --> 00:04:45,730
as circumstances require.

82
00:04:45,730 --> 00:04:48,350
Upon completion of duty, report back.
Assignments may be terminated at any time.

83
00:04:48,350 --> 00:04:50,480
This is the roster
of your Southern Archives.

84
00:04:48,620 --> 00:04:51,620
[Southern Archives Personnel Roster]

85
00:04:50,610 --> 00:04:52,130
A record of all the staff members.

86
00:04:51,640 --> 00:04:52,730
[Name: Zhang Ruifu] [Appointed as
Commissioner of the Southern Archives]

87
00:04:52,930 --> 00:04:55,180
How come everyone in your Archives

88
00:04:55,180 --> 00:04:56,870
is named Zhang?

89
00:04:56,870 --> 00:04:58,190
Is it a family business?

90
00:04:58,190 --> 00:05:00,450
My mentor said Zhang is a common surname—

91
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:02,090
it helps us blend in easily

92
00:05:02,090 --> 00:05:03,090
and go unnoticed.

93
00:05:03,510 --> 00:05:06,140
I changed my surname to Zhang
after being taken in.

94
00:05:06,140 --> 00:05:08,570
Maybe the Archives likes to
take in orphans.

95
00:05:08,570 --> 00:05:10,920
Seems like you're
a charitable organization.

96
00:05:10,920 --> 00:05:12,010
And I've noticed

97
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:15,000
you tend to favor older personnel.

98
00:05:12,460 --> 00:05:14,620
[Name: Zhang Jianbin] [Appointed as
Commissioner of the Southern Archives]

99
00:05:14,660 --> 00:05:16,440
[Name: Zhang Haini] [Appointed as
Commissioner of the Southern Archives]

100
00:05:15,030 --> 00:05:16,770
You really like hiring older staff.

101
00:05:16,770 --> 00:05:17,830
Well, we really do.

102
00:05:19,060 --> 00:05:20,780
Maybe the Zhangs just
tend to live longer.

103
00:05:20,780 --> 00:05:21,100
[Name: Zhang Ruiping] [Appointed as
Commissioner of the Southern Archives]

104
00:05:23,030 --> 00:05:23,890
What are these?

105
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:29,410
[Name: Zhang Haiqi] [Appointed as Director
of the Southern Archives]

106
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:28,930
Zhang Haiqi,
Director of the Southern Archives.

107
00:05:42,470 --> 00:05:44,820
[Xiacheng, Late Qing Dynasty]

108
00:05:55,350 --> 00:06:01,830
[Danan Telegraph Office]

109
00:05:55,740 --> 00:05:56,330
Yeah!

110
00:05:56,330 --> 00:05:57,430
Yeah!

111
00:05:57,810 --> 00:05:59,810
Danan Telegraph Office?

112
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:01,270
Yeah!

113
00:06:02,510 --> 00:06:03,450
Is a "telegraph office"

114
00:06:03,450 --> 00:06:05,300
what Westerners would call a post office?

115
00:06:05,080 --> 00:06:07,430
[Danan Telegraph Office]

116
00:06:05,300 --> 00:06:07,830
I heard Westerners practice
a kind of sorcery.

117
00:06:07,830 --> 00:06:10,410
They can summon the souls of the dead
from their graves

118
00:06:10,410 --> 00:06:12,210
and make them deliver messages.

119
00:06:12,300 --> 00:06:15,010
Their news can travel thousands of miles
in a single day.

120
00:06:15,010 --> 00:06:16,470
How is that even possible?

121
00:06:16,740 --> 00:06:18,380
Witchcraft. It has to be witchcraft.

122
00:06:18,380 --> 00:06:19,370
Yes.

123
00:06:19,450 --> 00:06:20,480
That's because

124
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:23,910
the telegraph wires are specifically
routed over graveyards.

125
00:06:23,910 --> 00:06:24,830
That's so unlucky.

126
00:06:24,030 --> 00:06:26,640
[Danan Telegraph Office]

127
00:06:24,870 --> 00:06:26,070
Go. Let's leave here.

128
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:27,240
Let's go, let's go.

129
00:06:29,980 --> 00:06:37,500
[Danan Telegraph Office]

130
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:33,840
Director,

131
00:06:34,450 --> 00:06:35,690
the soul-summoning stories

132
00:06:35,690 --> 00:06:38,020
have been spreading rapidly around here.

133
00:06:38,240 --> 00:06:40,950
The Southern Archives is being built
underground beneath a busy district.

134
00:06:40,950 --> 00:06:42,480
Some noise is unavoidable.

135
00:06:42,860 --> 00:06:44,700
Having civilians steer clear

136
00:06:45,070 --> 00:06:47,390
actually makes it easier
for us to operate.

137
00:06:47,390 --> 00:06:49,860
Spread a few more stories like that.

138
00:06:50,970 --> 00:06:51,409
Yes.

139
00:06:54,460 --> 00:06:56,490
[Danan Telegraph Office]

140
00:07:00,070 --> 00:07:01,800
Looks like I know nothing about

141
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:03,260
my mentor or the Archives.

142
00:07:09,530 --> 00:07:10,410
Put it back.

143
00:07:14,660 --> 00:07:16,620
Now that we've found what we came for,

144
00:07:16,620 --> 00:07:17,630
let's hurry

145
00:07:18,680 --> 00:07:19,770
and find a way out.

146
00:07:21,450 --> 00:07:23,510
I've only found the first item I need.

147
00:07:23,740 --> 00:07:24,900
You can leave if you want.

148
00:07:24,900 --> 00:07:25,850
Only one?

149
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:27,800
That won't do.

150
00:07:28,620 --> 00:07:30,980
According to the land deed,
the Southern Archives

151
00:07:30,980 --> 00:07:32,610
belongs to Haili Bank.

152
00:07:32,770 --> 00:07:34,860
Don't even think about wrecking the place.

153
00:07:34,860 --> 00:07:36,620
Once I've found what I need,

154
00:07:36,830 --> 00:07:37,690
this place is all yours.

155
00:07:37,690 --> 00:07:38,750
Oh, give me a break.

156
00:07:39,270 --> 00:07:41,890
From what I can tell, you don't know much
about the Archives either.

157
00:07:41,890 --> 00:07:43,300
You don't have a say.

158
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:49,420
Cousin.

159
00:07:50,750 --> 00:07:52,080
Do you smell something?

160
00:07:53,630 --> 00:07:54,740
Yes.

161
00:07:55,230 --> 00:07:57,360
Why is there such a strong moldy smell?

162
00:07:57,570 --> 00:07:58,900
You don't know about it?

163
00:08:18,330 --> 00:08:20,460
Something feels off about this place.

164
00:08:20,860 --> 00:08:21,680
Be careful.

165
00:09:48,500 --> 00:09:54,690
[Archives: The Nanyang Mystery]

166
00:09:55,170 --> 00:09:57,670
[Episode 14]

167
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:13,540
Be careful.

168
00:10:26,170 --> 00:10:27,790
What exactly happened here?

169
00:10:28,810 --> 00:10:31,340
Looks like it's been abandoned
for a very long time.

170
00:10:31,340 --> 00:10:33,060
There were moles here before.

171
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:34,770
That's why it was shut down.

172
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:37,050
And those moles could change their faces.

173
00:10:37,050 --> 00:10:38,220
So whenever we came here,

174
00:10:38,220 --> 00:10:40,050
we had to check each other's faces.

175
00:10:40,050 --> 00:10:40,740
Like this.

176
00:10:41,320 --> 00:10:41,980
Stop it.

177
00:10:43,410 --> 00:10:44,670
Your wound split open.

178
00:10:45,630 --> 00:10:46,130
Your...

179
00:10:46,130 --> 00:10:47,660
Your wound reopened too...

180
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:55,040
How did...

181
00:10:55,340 --> 00:10:57,510
How did both of our wounds split open?

182
00:11:01,640 --> 00:11:03,960
Do you know about
a certain kind of bat saliva?

183
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:05,670
Of course I don't!

184
00:11:05,820 --> 00:11:06,960
What should we do now?

185
00:11:06,960 --> 00:11:09,040
It keeps wounds from healing.

186
00:11:09,580 --> 00:11:10,250
I'm guessing

187
00:11:10,250 --> 00:11:11,860
the blades behind that jade gate earlier

188
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:13,250
were coated with that bat saliva.

189
00:11:13,250 --> 00:11:14,510
Plus, it's warm and humid here,

190
00:11:14,510 --> 00:11:15,770
so our wounds split open.

191
00:11:15,770 --> 00:11:16,890
T-Then what do we do now?

192
00:11:16,890 --> 00:11:18,220
The door here is locked.

193
00:11:18,530 --> 00:11:19,250
Let's go back first.

194
00:11:19,250 --> 00:11:20,810
Okay, okay. Let's go.

195
00:11:23,420 --> 00:11:24,020
Hurry.

196
00:11:25,070 --> 00:11:26,260
Help me, help me.

197
00:11:26,850 --> 00:11:27,420
Hurry.

198
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:32,460
What's wrong now?

199
00:11:34,050 --> 00:11:35,130
Do you know what a rat trap is?

200
00:11:35,130 --> 00:11:36,250
W-What do you mean?

201
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:39,080
We are the rats
caught inside it right now.

202
00:11:39,200 --> 00:11:39,950
What should we do?

203
00:11:39,950 --> 00:11:40,770
Don't panic.

204
00:11:41,150 --> 00:11:42,680
I'll figure something out.

205
00:11:45,480 --> 00:11:46,470
Hurry up.

206
00:11:48,010 --> 00:11:48,880
Well?

207
00:11:49,120 --> 00:11:50,250
Can you decipher it?

208
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:51,370
Can you?

209
00:11:51,370 --> 00:11:52,220
Can you decipher it?

210
00:11:52,220 --> 00:11:52,780
Be quiet.

211
00:11:52,910 --> 00:11:53,670
Isn't this the answer your buddy

212
00:11:53,670 --> 00:11:55,210
deliberately left for you?

213
00:11:55,240 --> 00:11:56,600
How can you still not figure it out?

214
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:57,980
Were you two even on the same wavelength?

215
00:11:57,980 --> 00:11:59,040
I said, be quiet!

216
00:11:59,580 --> 00:12:01,480
I don't mean to, but I'm scared!

217
00:12:01,820 --> 00:12:02,740
What should we do now?

218
00:12:02,740 --> 00:12:04,600
I'm too scared to shut up.

219
00:12:15,350 --> 00:12:16,410
What's happening?

220
00:12:16,410 --> 00:12:17,470
What's that?

221
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:23,900
What's that?

222
00:12:26,740 --> 00:12:28,200
Plague, what should we do?

223
00:12:35,300 --> 00:12:37,130
There must be
some special mechanism up there

224
00:12:37,130 --> 00:12:38,440
that creates a kind of

225
00:12:38,440 --> 00:12:40,510
negative-pressure vacuum in this space.

226
00:12:40,510 --> 00:12:42,710
Just like drawing blood with a syringe.

227
00:12:43,340 --> 00:12:44,570
I tried stabbing it with my knife.

228
00:12:44,570 --> 00:12:45,830
The surface is too hard

229
00:12:46,130 --> 00:12:47,290
to break through.

230
00:12:47,440 --> 00:12:48,520
So,

231
00:12:48,600 --> 00:12:50,350
the previous trap and this one

232
00:12:50,390 --> 00:12:51,520
are the same trap.

233
00:12:51,700 --> 00:12:53,270
The wounds we got earlier

234
00:12:53,270 --> 00:12:55,730
are meant to bleed us to death
in here, right?

235
00:12:56,410 --> 00:12:57,740
Very ingenious, right?

236
00:12:57,750 --> 00:12:58,960
As expected of Shrimpie.

237
00:12:58,960 --> 00:13:00,200
Are you insane?

238
00:13:00,410 --> 00:13:02,500
At a time like this,
you're still praising him?

239
00:13:02,500 --> 00:13:04,080
Think of a way out!

240
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:06,390
Your friend is going to get us killed.

241
00:13:08,080 --> 00:13:09,610
He used double encryption.

242
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:11,390
The first layer is two-square cipher.

243
00:13:11,390 --> 00:13:12,780
As for the second layer...

244
00:13:12,780 --> 00:13:14,640
I don't know which system he used.

245
00:13:15,210 --> 00:13:16,680
Quickly think of a way out.

246
00:13:17,030 --> 00:13:17,770
Did he

247
00:13:18,270 --> 00:13:20,200
say anything special

248
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:21,250
or mention

249
00:13:21,370 --> 00:13:22,200
any little...

250
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:23,510
little habits?

251
00:13:23,820 --> 00:13:24,420
Little...

252
00:13:25,100 --> 00:13:25,700
Little...

253
00:13:28,270 --> 00:13:29,670
If I die,

254
00:13:30,280 --> 00:13:31,420
who will save you?

255
00:13:37,770 --> 00:13:40,300
Were we really that bad
at reading each other?

256
00:13:46,780 --> 00:13:48,860
Our hideout for dividing the loot
is so well concealed.

257
00:13:48,860 --> 00:13:50,120
How did this cop know?

258
00:13:50,390 --> 00:13:52,910
You little brat, who sent you?

259
00:13:55,080 --> 00:13:56,270
Won't talk, huh?

260
00:13:56,940 --> 00:13:57,850
Go to hell!

261
00:14:00,510 --> 00:14:01,600
Police!

262
00:14:02,390 --> 00:14:03,840
You're surrounded!

263
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:05,650
Drop your weapons within one minute,

264
00:14:05,650 --> 00:14:07,250
and we will spare your lives.

265
00:14:11,250 --> 00:14:12,510
Didn't I tell you to leave first?

266
00:14:12,510 --> 00:14:13,650
No one's leaving!

267
00:14:44,480 --> 00:14:45,340
Where are they?

268
00:14:45,360 --> 00:14:47,070
Find them! Don't let them get away!

269
00:14:47,070 --> 00:14:47,480
Yes, boss!

270
00:14:47,480 --> 00:14:47,840
Yes!

271
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:49,030
Check over there!

272
00:14:49,340 --> 00:14:50,540
Why did you come back?

273
00:14:50,820 --> 00:14:51,790
Did you forget the rules?

274
00:14:51,790 --> 00:14:53,340
If I hadn't, you'd be dead.

275
00:14:56,510 --> 00:14:57,630
And coming back actually helped?

276
00:14:57,630 --> 00:14:58,460
I'd say it helped quite a bit.

277
00:14:58,460 --> 00:14:59,460
Check over there.

278
00:14:59,570 --> 00:15:00,180
Yes.

279
00:15:00,630 --> 00:15:02,090
Did you bring any weapons?

280
00:15:14,940 --> 00:15:15,580
Come at me!

281
00:16:33,950 --> 00:16:34,910
Don't let him get away!

282
00:16:34,910 --> 00:16:35,620
After him!

283
00:17:19,400 --> 00:17:20,220
You really think our secret code

284
00:17:20,220 --> 00:17:21,880
would be that easy to imitate?

285
00:17:22,010 --> 00:17:23,240
What secret code?

286
00:17:41,740 --> 00:17:43,070
You prepared the crate?

287
00:17:45,420 --> 00:17:47,640
How could you have
calculated everything so precisely?

288
00:17:47,640 --> 00:17:49,240
If you ever get into trouble,

289
00:17:49,270 --> 00:17:50,530
take three steps back.

290
00:17:50,770 --> 00:17:54,030
I'll be right behind you
to ensure you have a fallback plan.

291
00:17:56,050 --> 00:17:58,290
The second layer of code on this banknote

292
00:17:58,290 --> 00:17:59,460
uses a skip-pattern cipher.

293
00:17:59,460 --> 00:18:03,050
First, replace each letter with the one
three places earlier in the alphabet,

294
00:18:03,050 --> 00:18:05,200
then decode it with the two-square cipher.

295
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:05,960
D,

296
00:18:06,740 --> 00:18:07,460
R,

297
00:18:08,500 --> 00:18:09,270
Y.

298
00:18:11,290 --> 00:18:12,860
Drying file...

299
00:18:54,760 --> 00:18:55,650
What's wrong?

300
00:18:56,250 --> 00:18:56,890
Cousin,

301
00:18:57,790 --> 00:18:58,720
the door is open.

302
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:01,840
I'm not dead?

303
00:19:02,570 --> 00:19:03,340
Plague,

304
00:19:03,400 --> 00:19:04,560
help me, help me.

305
00:19:24,720 --> 00:19:26,850
I've found the second medicinal herb.

306
00:19:27,700 --> 00:19:28,570
One more left.

307
00:19:47,440 --> 00:19:48,200
Sir,

308
00:19:48,220 --> 00:19:49,680
we found something. Look!

309
00:20:00,850 --> 00:20:02,770
An underground passage again.

310
00:20:02,770 --> 00:20:04,500
You have committed grave sins.

311
00:20:08,130 --> 00:20:09,690
If you can make it out alive,

312
00:20:09,910 --> 00:20:11,040
you'll be pardoned.

313
00:20:11,090 --> 00:20:12,050
I'll let you go.

314
00:20:13,570 --> 00:20:15,090
But in all this time,

315
00:20:15,350 --> 00:20:16,460
no one has ever

316
00:20:16,460 --> 00:20:18,000
come out of there alive.

317
00:22:26,180 --> 00:22:27,810
Blow it open.

318
00:22:28,400 --> 00:22:28,980
Yes, sir!

319
00:22:53,370 --> 00:22:54,230
What happened?

320
00:22:55,920 --> 00:22:57,110
You did pretty well back there.

321
00:22:57,110 --> 00:23:00,040
For an ordinary person,
that was pretty impressive.

322
00:23:00,050 --> 00:23:02,580
So not dying is considered
a success now, huh?

323
00:23:02,680 --> 00:23:04,250
If it keeps going like this,

324
00:23:04,770 --> 00:23:06,370
I might not be able to keep up.

325
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:07,800
You chose this path yourself.

326
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:08,930
What else can you do?

327
00:23:11,470 --> 00:23:12,690
What's this?

328
00:23:14,070 --> 00:23:15,400
This is my compass.

329
00:23:17,530 --> 00:23:17,980
Sometimes,

330
00:23:17,980 --> 00:23:20,040
I really admire this friend of yours.

331
00:23:20,270 --> 00:23:21,930
Is all this really necessary?

332
00:23:22,220 --> 00:23:25,030
Did he have to make the clues
this complicated?

333
00:23:30,130 --> 00:23:30,760
Cousin,

334
00:23:31,270 --> 00:23:32,720
you seem particularly interested

335
00:23:32,720 --> 00:23:33,850
in our Archives.

336
00:23:34,240 --> 00:23:36,000
We happen to be short-handed recently.

337
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:37,730
Ever thought about joining us?

338
00:23:41,870 --> 00:23:43,730
I should just keep things simple.

339
00:23:44,400 --> 00:23:45,650
Living an ordinary life

340
00:23:45,650 --> 00:23:46,850
is good enough for me.

341
00:23:58,040 --> 00:23:59,700
Always forgetting things...

342
00:24:01,180 --> 00:24:02,000
The clue...

343
00:24:03,050 --> 00:24:03,840
Clue...

344
00:24:05,160 --> 00:24:05,950
Master...

345
00:24:06,790 --> 00:24:07,800
Our mentor?

346
00:24:09,270 --> 00:24:10,400
What does this mean?

347
00:24:15,380 --> 00:24:16,640
This cave is spacious.

348
00:24:17,010 --> 00:24:18,270
There's much more air.

349
00:24:20,310 --> 00:24:21,110
Here, Plague.

350
00:24:21,750 --> 00:24:22,570
Your clue.

351
00:24:22,940 --> 00:24:23,580
What clue?

352
00:24:23,740 --> 00:24:24,310
Here.

353
00:24:57,440 --> 00:24:58,500
You wanna study it?

354
00:24:58,720 --> 00:24:59,290
Okay.

355
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:18,500
So what's drawn on here

356
00:25:19,160 --> 00:25:20,550
are these cracks.

357
00:25:23,420 --> 00:25:25,290
[Double Clouds]

358
00:25:24,460 --> 00:25:26,200
Isn't "Double Clouds" the crack

359
00:25:26,200 --> 00:25:27,590
we just walked through?

360
00:25:27,130 --> 00:25:27,970
[Double Clouds]

361
00:25:28,510 --> 00:25:30,440
In ancient usage,
"double clouds" means eyes.

362
00:25:30,440 --> 00:25:31,700
So when we crawled through there,

363
00:25:31,700 --> 00:25:34,500
we had to keep our eyes wide open
without blinking.

364
00:25:36,830 --> 00:25:38,260
So these names

365
00:25:38,700 --> 00:25:40,940
describe the characteristics
of each passage.

366
00:25:40,940 --> 00:25:42,200
What about these?

367
00:25:57,680 --> 00:25:59,680
This one's called "Broken Dragon."

368
00:26:03,300 --> 00:26:04,750
[Ah Xiang]

369
00:26:08,530 --> 00:26:10,220
Now, this one is quite something.

370
00:26:10,220 --> 00:26:11,220
This one is called

371
00:26:11,400 --> 00:26:12,140
"Ah Xiang."

372
00:26:13,090 --> 00:26:13,830
Broken Dragon, Ah Xiang...

373
00:26:13,830 --> 00:26:15,680
Why do those names sound so rustic?

374
00:26:15,680 --> 00:26:16,290
Alright.

375
00:26:16,420 --> 00:26:18,080
Never mind if they're rustic.

376
00:26:18,350 --> 00:26:20,080
Well, which one should we take?

377
00:26:20,640 --> 00:26:22,700
Which one do you think we should take?

378
00:26:28,920 --> 00:26:29,740
Ah Xiang.

379
00:26:46,500 --> 00:26:47,010
Wait,

380
00:26:47,010 --> 00:26:47,720
why?

381
00:26:48,440 --> 00:26:49,970
How did you figure that out?

382
00:26:51,650 --> 00:26:52,210
Plague?

383
00:26:52,480 --> 00:26:53,010
Plague!

384
00:26:54,050 --> 00:26:56,780
How did you know
Broken Dragon was the right path?

385
00:26:57,290 --> 00:26:59,550
Because "Broken Dragon" sounds cooler.

386
00:27:00,720 --> 00:27:01,810
Fine, fine.

387
00:27:10,700 --> 00:27:12,360
Being cool does have its uses.

388
00:27:15,850 --> 00:27:16,710
Broken Dragon?

389
00:27:19,510 --> 00:27:20,960
What does that even mean?

390
00:27:25,920 --> 00:27:26,640
Plague,

391
00:27:27,880 --> 00:27:29,540
there's writing carved here.

392
00:27:38,680 --> 00:27:42,050
"Year 25, abnormal movements
were detected beneath Xiacheng.

393
00:27:42,050 --> 00:27:44,220
The Director of the Southern Archives

394
00:27:44,220 --> 00:27:45,810
followed the underground fissures downward

395
00:27:45,810 --> 00:27:47,610
and discovered the Underworld.

396
00:27:47,740 --> 00:27:50,270
Using feng shui
to suppress the dragon vein.

397
00:27:51,140 --> 00:27:53,500
As long as the underground dragon vein
of Xiacheng remains,

398
00:27:53,500 --> 00:27:55,160
seawater cannot flood inward,

399
00:27:55,160 --> 00:27:58,380
and the secret of the underground
remains hidden from the world.

400
00:27:58,380 --> 00:28:01,400
The Southern Archives was
subsequently established here

401
00:28:01,400 --> 00:28:03,460
to oversee all affairs of the South."

402
00:28:04,270 --> 00:28:06,850
We should be at
the very bottom boundary marker

403
00:28:06,850 --> 00:28:08,510
of the Southern Archives now.

404
00:28:13,530 --> 00:28:16,200
Behind this should be
the suppressed Underworld.

405
00:28:16,200 --> 00:28:17,380
The Underworld?

406
00:28:18,290 --> 00:28:20,030
Legend has it that the Archives
was built so deep

407
00:28:20,030 --> 00:28:22,010
in order to suppress
something underground.

408
00:28:22,010 --> 00:28:24,680
Then what does
"the secret of the underground" mean?

409
00:28:24,680 --> 00:28:26,240
The secret inside is crucial

410
00:28:26,240 --> 00:28:27,330
and must never be revealed.

411
00:28:27,330 --> 00:28:30,610
That's why they used two layers
of Dragon-Sealing Stones, inside and out,

412
00:28:30,610 --> 00:28:31,530
to keep it suppressed.

413
00:28:31,530 --> 00:28:33,380
Since it's a secret,

414
00:28:33,400 --> 00:28:35,030
why carve it onto a stone monument?

415
00:28:35,030 --> 00:28:36,560
And spell it out so clearly?

416
00:28:37,570 --> 00:28:38,600
It's a warning

417
00:28:39,680 --> 00:28:42,750
to tell people what's inside is
even more dangerous than what's outside.

418
00:28:42,750 --> 00:28:45,150
Looks like what I'm looking for
is in there.

419
00:28:47,480 --> 00:28:48,660
Is this a switch?

420
00:28:49,770 --> 00:28:50,770
It's really ugly.

421
00:29:43,590 --> 00:29:44,320
Sir.

422
00:29:47,520 --> 00:29:49,240
What's the situation down there?

423
00:29:49,240 --> 00:29:50,710
Three Maxim guns.

424
00:29:51,070 --> 00:29:52,090
Maxim guns?

425
00:29:53,670 --> 00:29:54,900
What do we do now, sir?

426
00:29:55,550 --> 00:29:58,350
Zhang Haiqi really
has everything planned out.

427
00:29:59,140 --> 00:30:01,730
She's using the Maxim machine guns

428
00:30:01,940 --> 00:30:03,180
to buy time

429
00:30:03,770 --> 00:30:06,570
until reinforcements arrive
from the consulate.

430
00:30:15,640 --> 00:30:16,720
But the Commander said

431
00:30:16,720 --> 00:30:17,790
that without his permission,

432
00:30:17,790 --> 00:30:19,190
we absolutely cannot...

433
00:30:20,380 --> 00:30:20,940
Sir...

434
00:30:21,480 --> 00:30:23,240
Go back and get it.

435
00:30:41,750 --> 00:30:43,770
After that gunfire, no one was left.

436
00:30:43,770 --> 00:30:44,680
If they can't figure out a way,

437
00:30:44,680 --> 00:30:46,480
they'll have to escape!

438
00:30:46,500 --> 00:30:47,690
Come on, boys!

439
00:30:48,070 --> 00:30:48,960
Pack up

440
00:30:48,960 --> 00:30:49,810
all these treasures!

441
00:30:49,810 --> 00:30:51,470
There's a share for everyone!

442
00:30:54,940 --> 00:30:56,010
Miss Dong,

443
00:30:56,090 --> 00:30:57,500
you really dug deep
into your pockets this time.

444
00:30:57,500 --> 00:30:58,760
I'd say we're even now.

445
00:30:58,790 --> 00:31:00,330
It's been a pleasure working with you.

446
00:31:00,330 --> 00:31:01,750
Don't celebrate too soon.

447
00:31:01,750 --> 00:31:04,010
Lu Junxiang won't just give up like that.

448
00:31:05,830 --> 00:31:08,200
Is that so? My Maxim guns might

449
00:31:08,200 --> 00:31:10,060
have something to say about that.

450
00:31:59,510 --> 00:32:01,440
I've put up with you for a long time.

451
00:32:01,570 --> 00:32:02,980
When did you find out?

452
00:32:03,570 --> 00:32:05,950
I can smell blood on people.

453
00:32:06,220 --> 00:32:07,480
You've killed people,

454
00:32:07,510 --> 00:32:09,050
but He Jianxi hasn't.

455
00:32:09,050 --> 00:32:10,310
Just based on that?

456
00:32:10,960 --> 00:32:12,220
Are you a dog?

457
00:32:13,460 --> 00:32:15,660
Mostly because your acting was terrible.

458
00:32:15,660 --> 00:32:17,640
He Jianxi has
an unusually keen sense of smell.

459
00:32:17,640 --> 00:32:19,510
But at the Bronze Ball Mechanism,

460
00:32:19,510 --> 00:32:21,880
you actually smelled that gunpowder
later than I did.

461
00:32:21,880 --> 00:32:23,310
Then forget looking for a key.

462
00:32:23,310 --> 00:32:25,170
Let's just break the door open.

463
00:32:27,510 --> 00:32:28,970
There's a smell of sulfur,

464
00:32:29,330 --> 00:32:31,330
so there must be explosives inside.

465
00:32:32,340 --> 00:32:33,280
It really is.

466
00:32:33,510 --> 00:32:34,320
That's when I knew

467
00:32:34,320 --> 00:32:35,840
you weren't He Jianxi.

468
00:32:36,480 --> 00:32:39,810
And the most ridiculous part is
that you somehow got taller.

469
00:32:51,070 --> 00:32:52,310
Then why

470
00:32:53,090 --> 00:32:54,820
didn't you act on it at the time?

471
00:32:55,180 --> 00:32:56,740
If I'd killed you then,

472
00:32:56,940 --> 00:32:59,180
who would've kept me entertained
along the way?

473
00:32:59,180 --> 00:33:00,350
I'd have been bored to death.

474
00:33:00,350 --> 00:33:01,060
Besides,

475
00:33:01,440 --> 00:33:02,050
I wasn't sure

476
00:33:02,050 --> 00:33:03,910
whether you were sent by my mentor

477
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:05,860
or by the enemies of the Archives.

478
00:33:06,110 --> 00:33:07,230
After all, you did save me once

479
00:33:07,230 --> 00:33:08,760
and got the medicine for me.

480
00:33:09,720 --> 00:33:10,890
I promised my mentor

481
00:33:11,700 --> 00:33:13,500
I'd break this bad habit of mine.

482
00:33:19,590 --> 00:33:21,020
So you're saying

483
00:33:22,030 --> 00:33:24,090
you were risking your life to test me?

484
00:33:25,240 --> 00:33:27,570
Is everyone from the Archives this crazy?

485
00:33:28,220 --> 00:33:29,280
Where is my cousin?

486
00:33:29,400 --> 00:33:30,300
He's fine.

487
00:33:34,140 --> 00:33:34,920
That's good.

488
00:33:36,980 --> 00:33:38,440
Since you've attacked me,

489
00:33:39,100 --> 00:33:41,430
you definitely weren't sent by my mentor.

490
00:33:42,190 --> 00:33:43,040
So now...

491
00:33:44,790 --> 00:33:45,660
you can die.

492
00:34:00,180 --> 00:34:01,500
You spy,

493
00:34:01,500 --> 00:34:02,650
drop the act.

494
00:34:03,050 --> 00:34:04,510
Where did those banknotes come from?

495
00:34:04,510 --> 00:34:05,570
What are you trying to get inside there?

496
00:34:05,570 --> 00:34:06,550
You bastard,

497
00:34:06,550 --> 00:34:09,280
how dare you pretend to be
a good guy in front of me?

498
00:36:08,070 --> 00:36:09,600
Sir, no sign of Zhang Haiqi.

499
00:36:11,870 --> 00:36:13,680
What a pity.

500
00:36:24,340 --> 00:36:26,180
Sir! Sir!

501
00:36:26,480 --> 00:36:27,470
Bad news, sir!

502
00:36:28,570 --> 00:36:30,070
The outer underground structure
has completely collapsed!

503
00:36:30,070 --> 00:36:31,800
Huge amounts of seawater are pouring in!

504
00:36:31,800 --> 00:36:32,960
If we don't leave now,

505
00:36:32,960 --> 00:36:34,420
we'll all drown down here!

506
00:36:40,210 --> 00:36:42,730
Keep pursuing Zhang Haiqi!

507
00:36:42,730 --> 00:36:43,560
Yes, sir!

508
00:36:47,760 --> 00:36:50,290
Zhang Hailou,
you've finally made it inside.

509
00:36:50,480 --> 00:36:51,900
But you're out of time.

510
00:36:52,630 --> 00:36:53,970
The Archives is about to be flooded.
